var note1 = "What is Peter saying to us in verse 8? \n \n In verses 5-7, Peter list seven things that must be added to our faith, and when added, will produce fruit in our lives: \n 5 And beside this, giving all diligence, add to your faith virtue; and to virtue knowledge; 6 And to knowledge temperance; and to temperance patience; and to patience godliness; 7 And to godliness brotherly kindness; and to brotherly kindness charity.  \n \n Faith is the foundation for the seven qualities Peter lists. He instructs us “to add to our faith.” Our faith must be more than belief in certain biblical facts; our faith must result in action.  Let’s go to Hebrews 11 and look at a few biblical figures whose faith produced action. \n  \n 1.  Heb. 11:4 – By faith Abel __________________. \n\n 2.  Heb. 11:5 – By faith Enoch _________________. \n\n 3.  Heb. 11:7 – By faith Noah __________________. \n\n 4.  Heb. 11:8 – By faith Abraham _______________. \n\n According to Peter, this is the type of faith that should be the foundation of our Christian experience and when we add the seven qualities, we will be fruitful. \n \n The Seven Qualities of a Fruitful Christian \n\n 1. to your faith add virtue/moral excellence: \n\n Mark 5:30 \n\n 2. to your virtue add knowledge: \n\n 2 Timothy 2:15 \n\n 3. to knowledge add temperance/self-control: \n\n Philippians 4:7 \n\n 4. to temperance add patience/perseverance: \n\n Isaiah 40:31 \n\n 5. to patience add godliness: serious and faithful in the worship of God. \n\n 1 Timothy 4:8 \n\n  Forms of worship:  \n\n 5. to godliness add brotherly kindness:  \n\n Acts 28:2  \n\n  6. to brotherly kindness add charity/love:  \n\n  John 17:26  \n \n  \n For if these things be in you, and abound, they make you that ye shall neither be barren nor unfruitful in the knowledge of our Lord Jesus Christ. (KJV)  \n  \n \n For if these qualities are yours and are increasing, they render you neither useless nor unfruitful in the true knowledge of our Lord Jesus Christ. (NASB)"

var note2 = "Thesis: This text is tailored to teach us that in the difficult seasons of our lives, we must choose to see God in the unheralded experiences of our lives.  \n   \n 1. God can be seen in what He has prevented from happening to you (6:1).  \n   \n 2. God can be seen in what He sees in you (6:11-12).  \n   \n 3. God can be seen in what He promises to you (6:15-16)."










